Middleware in Express.js are functions that execute during the request-response cycle. They have access to the request object (req), response object (res), and the next() function.

Syntax: function(req, res, next) { ... next(); }

Types of Middleware:
1. Application-level: app.use() or app.get()
2. Router-level: router.use()
3. Error-handling: function(err, req, res, next)
4. Built-in: express.json(), express.static()
5. Third-party: body-parser, cors, etc.

Example:
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

// Middleware function
const logger = (req, res, next) => {
  console.log(`${req.method} ${req.url}`);
  next(); // Pass control to next middleware
};

app.use(logger);

app.get('/', (req, res) => {
  res.send('Home Page');
});

app.listen(3000);

Middleware is used to: log requests, parse request bodies, authenticate users, handle CORS, serve static files, etc.

