In Express.js, you can send different types of responses:

1. Sending HTML Response:
app.get('/html', (req, res) => {
  res.set('Content-Type', 'text/html');
  res.send('<h1>Hello from Express</h1><p>This is HTML</p>');
});
// OR using res.sendFile() for an HTML file:
// res.sendFile(path.join(__dirname, 'index.html'));

2. Sending JSON Response:
app.get('/json', (req, res) => {
  const data = { name: 'LJU', course: 'FSD-2', year: 2026 };
  res.json(data);
  // res.json() automatically sets Content-Type to application/json
});

3. Difference:
- res.send() with HTML string sends text/html
- res.json() converts a JS object to JSON string and sets proper headers automatically
- res.set('Content-Type','application/json') + res.send(JSON.stringify(obj)) is equivalent to res.json(obj)
